{"title_page": "Ander Barrenetxea (footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish professional footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{For|the cyclist|Ander Barrenetxea Uriarte}}\n{{Spanish name|Barrenetxea|Muguruza}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ander Barrenetxea\n| image = CSC 0017 (32672683418) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Barrenetxea training with Real Sociedad, 2018\n| full_name = Ander Barrenetxea Muguruza\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], Spain\n| height = 1.78 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Real Sociedad]]\n| clubnumber = 22\n| youthyears1 = 2011\u20132013 | youthclubs1 = [[Antiguoko]]<ref name=camino/><ref name=anderperu/>\n| youthyears2 = 2013\u20132018 | youthclubs2 = [[Real Sociedad cantera|Real Sociedad]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Antiguoko/status/340871580970254337|title=RealSociedad ha fichado a los jugadores de Antiguoko para la 13/14, Jesus Owono, Ander Barrenetxea,Jon Sanchez y Martin Zubimendi,Zorionak|publisher=[[Antiguoko]]|via=[[Twitter]]|date=1 June 2013|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n| years1 = 2018\u20132019 | clubs1 = [[Real Sociedad C]] | caps1 = 4 | goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2018\u2013 | clubs2 = [[Real Sociedad]] | caps2 = 10 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2019 | clubs3 = [[Real Sociedad B]] | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2018\u20132019 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update = 19 May 2019\n| nationalteam-update = 27 July 2019\n}}\n\n'''Ander Barrenetxea Muguruza''' (born 27 December 2001) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Real Sociedad]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], [[Gipuzkoa]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Barrenetxea is a graduate of [[Real Sociedad]]'s youth setup.\n\nIn the [[2018\u201319 Real Sociedad season|2018\u201319 season]], he began to become involved in training with the senior team, while registered with the club's [[Real Sociedad C|C-team]] playing in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|amateur fourth tier]]. In early December 2018, he renewed his contract until 2025.<ref name=contractDec18>{{Cite web|url=https://fundazioa.realsociedad.eus/es/f/noticias/detalle/amplia-su-compromiso-hasta-2025\n|title=Ampl\u00eda su compromiso hasta 2025|trans-title=Extended his link until 2025|language=es |publisher=Real Sociedad|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December 2018, Barrenetxea made his professional and [[La Liga]] debut as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 1\u20130 home loss against [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]]. In so doing, he became the first player born in the [[21st century]] to appear in the competition,<ref name=marcafirst>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/12/22/5c1d731de5fdea7d7b8b45ee.html|title=Barrenetxea becomes the first player born in the 21st century to play in LaLiga Santander|work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=22 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref name=paisdebut>{{Cite web\n|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2018/12/22/actualidad/1545479623_686019.html|title=Debuta en LaLiga el primer futbolista nacido en el siglo XXI |trans-title=First LaLiga debut for a footballer born in the 21st century|language=es|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> the 26th-youngest debutant in the division overall, and Real Sociedad's youngest since the [[Spanish Civil War]] (behind only 15-year-old [[Pedro Irastorza]] in 1934).<ref name=md26>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/laliga/20181222/453685516916/real-sociedad-barrenetxea-debut-historia-liga.html |title=Barrenetxea, el 26\u00ba debutante m\u00e1s joven de la historia de la Liga|trans-title=Barrenetxea, the 26th youngest debutant in the history of the League|language=es |work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|date=22 December 2018 |accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>  By coincidence, the player who left the field, [[Juanmi (footballer, born 1993)|Juanmi]], was even younger when making his bow in the competition eight years earlier.<ref name=md26/>\n\nBarrenetxea's rapid progression to the senior team made him the first youth product to appear at that level without already playing for the club's [[Real Sociedad B|B-team]], since [[Antoine Griezmann]] did so in 2009.<ref name=camino>{{Cite web |url=https://www.noticiasdegipuzkoa.eus/2018/12/24/la-real/el-camino-de-las-estrellas|title=El camino de las estrellas|trans-title=The way of the stars|language=es|work=Noticias de Gipuzkoa|date=24 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> Two days after his breakthrough, he was back playing with the C-team.<ref name=marcafourth>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/12/23/5c1fecc322601de55a8b456d.html|title=Real Sociedad starlet Barrenetxea goes from top flight to fourth tier in 48 hours|work=Marca|date=22 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBarrenetxea made his debut for Sanse on 6 January 2019, scoring on his debut in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third tier]] in a 3\u20130 home victory over [[CD Izarra]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.grada3.com/2019/01/06/cronica-sanse-izarra/|title=Barrenetxea, Roberto L\u00f3pez y Olaizola hacen de Reyes Magos|trans-title=Barrenetxea, Roberto L\u00f3pez and Olaizola are the Wise Men |language=es|work=Grada 3|date=6 January 2019|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal for the first team on 12 May, in a 3\u20131 home victory over [[Real Madrid CF]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=521558|title=Real Sociedad vs. Real Madrid - Football Match Report|date=12 May 2019|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2019, Barrenetxea was definitely promoted to the main squad of the ''Txuri-urdin''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/promote-to-the-first-team|title=Promote to the first team|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBarrenetxea was called up for the [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain Under-16 team]] in 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/es/noticias/detalle/ander-barrenetxea-convocado-con-la-sub-16|title=Ander Barrenetxea, convocado con la sub-16|trans-title=Ander Barrenetxea, summoned to the under-16s|language=es|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> and 2017,<ref name=anderperu>{{Cite web |url=https://real-sociedad.diariovasco.com/noticias/201703/29/ander-barrenetxea-peru-ruiz-20170329001401-v.html|title=Ander Barrenetxea y Peru Ruiz, con la sub-16|trans-title=Ander Barrenetxea and Peru Ruiz, with the under-16s|language=es|work=[[Diario Vasco]]|date=29 March 2017|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> and appeared for the [[Spain national under-18 football team|Under-18s]] in November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/match-report-second-win-spain-against-china-2-0 |title=Match Report: Second win for Spain against China (2-0) |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |website=Sefutbol |date=22 November 2018 |accessdate=24 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430063403/https://www.sefutbol.com/en/match-report-second-win-spain-against-china-2-0 |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He also featured for the regional [[Basque Football Federation|Basque Country]] in the same age groups.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kirolak.net/es/noticias_detalle.asp?volver=1&id=561&deporte=futbol&iddeporte=futbol|title=Convocatoria selecci\u00f3n de Euskadi sub 18 y 16 Masculina |trans-title=Call for Euskadi under 18 and under 16 Mens selections |language=es|publisher=Kirolak|date=23 December 2016|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2018/12/22/actualidad/1545479623_686019.html|title=Tres victorias y una derrota para Euskadi en la 1\u00aa fase disputada en Navarra|trans-title=Three victories and one defeat for Euskadi in the first phase played in Navarra|language=es|website=La Cantera de Lezama|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHe was selected for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship squads#Spain|20-man Spain squad]] for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. Barrenetxea came on as an 80th minute substitution as Spain beat Portugal 2\u20130 in the finals to be crowned winners of the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/news/0257-0dee769d9719-c61a7e965fcc-1000--spain-win-2019-u19-euro-at-a-glance/|title=Spain win 2019 U19 EURO: at a glance|date=2019-07-27|website=UEFA.com|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===International===\n;Spain U19\n*[[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]: Champion [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2019]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|22759}}\n*{{Soccerway|ander-barrenetxea-muguruza/587199}}\n*{{LaPreferente|266678<!-- /barrenetxea -->}}\n\n{{Real Sociedad squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrenetxea, Ander}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad B footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad C footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Antiguoko players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish professional footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{For|the cyclist|Ander Barrenetxea Uriarte}}\n{{Spanish name|Barrenetxea|Muguruza}}\n{{Infobox football biography \n| name = Ander Barrenetxea\n| image = CSC 0017 (32672683418) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Barrenetxea training with Real Sociedad, 2018\n| fullname = Ander Barrenetxea Muguruza\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], Spain\n| height = 1.78 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Real Sociedad]]\n| clubnumber = 22\n| youthyears1 = 2011\u20132013 | youthclubs1 = [[Antiguoko]]<ref name=camino/><ref name=anderperu/>\n| youthyears2 = 2013\u20132018 | youthclubs2 = [[Real Sociedad cantera|Real Sociedad]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Antiguoko/status/340871580970254337|title=RealSociedad ha fichado a los jugadores de Antiguoko para la 13/14, Jesus Owono, Ander Barrenetxea,Jon Sanchez y Martin Zubimendi,Zorionak|publisher=[[Antiguoko]]|via=[[Twitter]]|date=1 June 2013|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n| years1 = 2018\u20132019 | clubs1 = [[Real Sociedad C]] | caps1 = 4 | goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2018\u2013 | clubs2 = [[Real Sociedad]] | caps2 = 10 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2019 | clubs3 = [[Real Sociedad B]] | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2018\u20132019 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0  \n| club-update = 19 May 2019\n| nationalteam-update = 27 July 2019\n}}\n'''Ander Barrenetxea Muguruza''' (born 27 December 2001) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Real Sociedad]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]], [[Gipuzkoa]], [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Barrenetxea is a graduate of [[Real Sociedad]]'s youth setup.\n\nIn the [[2018\u201319 Real Sociedad season|2018\u201319 season]], he began to become involved in training with the senior team, while registered with the club's [[Real Sociedad C|C-team]] playing in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|amateur fourth tier]]. In early December 2018, he renewed his contract until 2025.<ref name=contractDec18>{{Cite web|url=https://fundazioa.realsociedad.eus/es/f/noticias/detalle/amplia-su-compromiso-hasta-2025\n|title=Ampl\u00eda su compromiso hasta 2025|trans-title=Extended his link until 2025|language=es |publisher=Real Sociedad|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December 2018, Barrenetxea made his professional and [[La Liga]] debut as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 1\u20130 home loss against [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]]. In so doing, he became the first player born in the [[21st century]] to appear in the competition,<ref name=marcafirst>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/12/22/5c1d731de5fdea7d7b8b45ee.html|title=Barrenetxea becomes the first player born in the 21st century to play in LaLiga Santander|work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=22 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref name=paisdebut>{{Cite web \n|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2018/12/22/actualidad/1545479623_686019.html|title=Debuta en LaLiga el primer futbolista nacido en el siglo XXI |trans-title=First LaLiga debut for a footballer born in the 21st century|language=es|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> the 26th-youngest debutant in the division overall, and Real Sociedad's youngest since the [[Spanish Civil War]] (behind only 15-year-old [[Pedro Irastorza]] in 1934).<ref name=md26>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/laliga/20181222/453685516916/real-sociedad-barrenetxea-debut-historia-liga.html |title=Barrenetxea, el 26\u00ba debutante m\u00e1s joven de la historia de la Liga|trans-title=Barrenetxea, the 26th youngest debutant in the history of the League|language=es |work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|date=22 December 2018 |accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>  By coincidence, the player who left the field, [[Juanmi (footballer, born 1993)|Juanmi]], was even younger when making his bow in the competition eight years earlier.<ref name=md26/>\n\nBarrenetxea's rapid progression to the senior team made him the first youth product to appear at that level without already playing for the club's [[Real Sociedad B|B-team]], since [[Antoine Griezmann]] did so in 2009.<ref name=camino>{{Cite web |url=https://www.noticiasdegipuzkoa.eus/2018/12/24/la-real/el-camino-de-las-estrellas|title=El camino de las estrellas|trans-title=The way of the stars|language=es|work=Noticias de Gipuzkoa|date=24 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> Two days after his breakthrough, he was back playing with the C-team.<ref name=marcafourth>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2018/12/23/5c1fecc322601de55a8b456d.html|title=Real Sociedad starlet Barrenetxea goes from top flight to fourth tier in 48 hours|work=Marca|date=22 December 2018|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBarrenetxea made his debut for Sanse on 6 January 2019, scoring on his debut in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third tier]] in a 3\u20130 home victory over [[CD Izarra]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.grada3.com/2019/01/06/cronica-sanse-izarra/|title=Barrenetxea, Roberto L\u00f3pez y Olaizola hacen de Reyes Magos|trans-title=Barrenetxea, Roberto L\u00f3pez and Olaizola are the Wise Men |language=es|work=Grada 3|date=6 January 2019|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal for the first team on 12 May, in a 3\u20131 home victory over [[Real Madrid CF]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=521558|title=Real Sociedad vs. Real Madrid - Football Match Report|date=12 May 2019|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2019, Barrenetxea was definitely promoted to the main squad of the ''Txuri-urdin''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/promote-to-the-first-team|title=Promote to the first team|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=9 June 2019|accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBarrenetxea was called up for the [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain Under-16 team]] in 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/es/noticias/detalle/ander-barrenetxea-convocado-con-la-sub-16|title=Ander Barrenetxea, convocado con la sub-16|trans-title=Ander Barrenetxea, summoned to the under-16s|language=es|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> and 2017,<ref name=anderperu>{{Cite web |url=https://real-sociedad.diariovasco.com/noticias/201703/29/ander-barrenetxea-peru-ruiz-20170329001401-v.html|title=Ander Barrenetxea y Peru Ruiz, con la sub-16|trans-title=Ander Barrenetxea and Peru Ruiz, with the under-16s|language=es|work=[[Diario Vasco]]|date=29 March 2017|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref> and appeared for the [[Spain national under-18 football team|Under-18s]] in November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/match-report-second-win-spain-against-china-2-0 |title=Match Report: Second win for Spain against China (2-0) |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |website=Sefutbol |date=22 November 2018 |accessdate=24 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430063403/https://www.sefutbol.com/en/match-report-second-win-spain-against-china-2-0 |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He also featured for the regional [[Basque Football Federation|Basque Country]] in the same age groups.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kirolak.net/es/noticias_detalle.asp?volver=1&id=561&deporte=futbol&iddeporte=futbol|title=Convocatoria selecci\u00f3n de Euskadi sub 18 y 16 Masculina |trans-title=Call for Euskadi under 18 and under 16 Mens selections |language=es|publisher=Kirolak|date=23 December 2016|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2018/12/22/actualidad/1545479623_686019.html|title=Tres victorias y una derrota para Euskadi en la 1\u00aa fase disputada en Navarra|trans-title=Three victories and one defeat for Euskadi in the first phase played in Navarra|language=es|website=La Cantera de Lezama|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHe was selected for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship squads#Spain|20-man Spain squad]] for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. Barrenetxea came on as an 80th minute substitution as Spain beat Portugal 2\u20130 in the finals to be crowned winners of the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/news/0257-0dee769d9719-c61a7e965fcc-1000--spain-win-2019-u19-euro-at-a-glance/|title=Spain win 2019 U19 EURO: at a glance|date=2019-07-27|website=UEFA.com|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> \n\n==Honours==\n===International===\n;Spain U19\n*[[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]: Champion [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2019]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|22759}}\n*{{Soccerway|ander-barrenetxea-muguruza/587199}}\n*{{LaPreferente|266678/barrenetxea}}\n\n{{Real Sociedad squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrenetxea, Ander}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad B footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad C footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Antiguoko players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update links, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ander_Barrenetxea_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Houttuynia cordata", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Houttuynia_cordata.jpg\n|genus = Houttuynia\n|species = cordata\n|authority = Thunb.\n}}\n\n'''''Houttuynia cordata''''', also known as '''fish mint''', '''fish leaf''', '''rainbow plant''', '''chameleon plant''', '''heart leaf''',  '''fish wort''', '''Chinese lizard tail''', or '''bishop's weed''', is one of two species in the genus ''[[Houttuynia]]'' (the other being ''H.&nbsp;emeiensis''). It is a [[flowering plant]] native to [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=\"rhs\">{{cite web|title=''Houttuynia cordata'', Thunb.|url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:927252-1|publisher=KewScience, The Royal Horticultural Society, UK|accessdate=8 October 2018|date=2018}}</ref> It grows in moist, shady locations.<ref name=\"pfaf\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pfaf.org/user/plant.aspx?latinname=Houttuynia+cordata |title=''Houttuynia cordata'' Thunb.|publisher=Plants for a Future|date=2012|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Growth==\n''Houttuynia cordata'' is a [[herbaceous]] [[perennial plant]] that can grow to {{convert|0.6|-|1|m|ft}}, spreading up to {{convert|1|m|ft}}.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> The proximal part of the stem is trailing and produces [[adventitious root]]s, while the distal part of the stem grows vertically. The [[Leaf|leaves]] are alternate, broadly heart-shaped, {{convert|4-9|cm|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|3-8|cm|abbr=on}} broad. Its [[flower]]s are greenish-yellow and borne on a terminal spike {{convert|2\u20133|cm|abbr=on}} long with four to six large white basal [[bract]]s.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> It normally blooms in the summer.\n\n==Cultivation==\n[[File:Houttuynia cordata Chameleon.jpg|thumb|right|''Houttuynia cordata'' 'Chameleon']]\n''Houttuynia cordata'' grows in moist to wet soil or slightly submerged in water, as long as it is exposed partially or fully to the sun.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> It can become invasive in gardens and difficult to eradicate. It propagates by division.\n\nIt is usually found in one of its cultivated forms in temperate gardens. The ''''Chameleon'''' variety (synonymous with ''H.cordata'' 'Court Jester',  'Tricolour', and 'Variegata') is slightly less vigorous than the parent species, with stubbier leaves mottled in both yellow and red. Another common variety, ''''Flore Pleno'''', has masses of white bracts and retains the vigor of the parent species.\n\n''Houttuynia cordata'' has been naturalized in North America.<ref>[http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?si=854 Global Invasive Species Database:  Houttuynia cordata], accessed 2008-07-06</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\n\n=== Culinary use ===\n[[File:Yakmomil-kkot-cha.jpg|thumb|Flowers picked for ''yakmomil-kkot-cha'' (flower tea) in ''[[sokuri]]'']]\nIt is commonly grown as a [[leaf vegetable]], and is used as a fresh herbal [[garnish (food)|garnish]].<ref name=pfaf/> The leaf has an unusual taste that is often described as 'fishy' (earning it the nickname \"fish mint\"), so it is not enjoyed as universally as basil, mint, or other more commonly used herbs.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn northeastern India, it is commonly used in salads, salsas, or cooked with other vegetables, and as a garnish over side dishes.The tender roots can also be ground into chutneys along with dry fish, chilies, and tamarind. It is taken raw as salad and cooked along with fish as fish curry. In Japan and Korea, its dried leaves may be used as a tea.\n\nIn Vietnamese cuisine, it is called di\u1ebfp c\u00e1, and it is used with grilled meat and noodle salad dishes.<ref name=\"herbs\">[https://vietherbs.com/herb-directory/fish-herb/ Vietnamese Herbs: Fish Mint], Accessed October 9, 2018.</ref> Fish mint may be used as a garnish with several Vietnamese dishes, such as [[g\u1ecfi cu\u1ed1n]] stir-fried beef with fish mint salad,<ref>[https://www.sunset.com/food-wine/5-delicious-vietnamese-herbs-to-grow-and-eat Sunset: 5 Delicious Vietnamese Herbs to Grow and Eat], Accessed October 9, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://cookpad.com/vn/tim-kiem/rau%20di%E1%BA%BFp%20c%C3%A1 Cookpad, CookBook Inc.], Accessed October 9, 2018</ref> and [[b\u00e1nh x\u00e8o]].<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2011/10/18/141470565/banh-xeo-sizzling-crepes, NPR Inc.:Banh Xeo (Sizzling Crepes)], Accessed October 10, 2018</ref>\n\n====Zhe'ergen====\n[[File:Houttuynia_roots_vegetable_china.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Zhe'ergen is often served as a cold salad after being washed, diced and tossed with sauces derived from vinegar, chilli, coriander and soy sauce.]]\n'''Zh\u00e9'\u011brg\u0113n''' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u6298\u8033\u6839) is the edible rhizome of ''Houttuynia cordata'' ('''Yuxingcao''', \u9c7c\u8165\u8349 \u2018fish smelling leaf\u2019) with a fresh, spicy, peppery flavour that is used in southwestern Chinese cuisine, i.e. that of [[Guizhou]], [[Sichuan]], [[Yunnan]] and western [[Guangxi]]. Typically the leaves are eaten in Sichuan and the root in Guizhou. Zh\u00e9'\u011brg\u0113n fried with cured \u2018la rou\u2019 (a dried meat resembling \u2018Chinese bacon\u2019) is one of the staple dishes of Guizhou.\n\nNotable uses include:\n*part of the extensive [[fried rice]] cuisine of [[Guizhou]]\n*a condiment to ''[[migan (noodle)|migan]]'' and ''[[mixian (noodle)|mixian]]'' noodles when served in broth\n*as a component of dipping sauces used with the [[Shiping]] and [[Jianshui]] tradition of barbecued tofu\n*raw consumption as part of cold-tossed salads, when it is most frequently combined with [[coriander]], [[vinegar]], fresh [[Chili pepper|chilli]], and [[soy sauce]].\n\nThe leaves are also a little peppery and are frequently consumed in the region.\n\n=== Traditional medicine ===\n''Houttuynia cordata'' was used in [[traditional Chinese medicine]], including by Chinese scientists in an attempt to treat [[SARS]]<ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=18479853|year=2008|author1=Lau|first1=K. M|title=Immunomodulatory and anti-SARS activities of ''Houttuynia cordata''|journal=Journal of Ethnopharmacology|volume=118|issue=1|pages=79\u201385|last2=Lee|first2=K. M|last3=Koon|first3=C. M|last4=Cheung|first4=C. S|last5=Lau|first5=C. P|last6=Ho|first6=H. M|last7=Lee|first7=M. Y|last8=Au|first8=S. W|last9=Cheng|first9=C. H|last10=Lau|first10=C. B|last11=Tsui|first11=S. K|last12=Wan|first12=D. C|last13=Waye|first13=M. M|last14=Wong|first14=K. B|last15=Wong|first15=C. K|last16=Lam|first16=C. W|last17=Leung|first17=P. C|last18=Fung|first18=K. P|doi=10.1016/j.jep.2008.03.018}}</ref> and various other disorders,<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=3931198|year=2014|author1=Kumar|first1=M|title=A current update on the phytopharmacological aspects of ''Houttuynia cordata'' Thunb|journal=Pharmacognosy Reviews|volume=8|issue=15|pages=22\u201335|last2=Prasad|first2=S. K|last3=Hemalatha|first3=S|doi=10.4103/0973-7847.125525|pmid=24600193}}</ref> although there is no high-quality [[clinical research]] to confirm such uses are safe or effective, as of 2018. When administered via injection, ''H. cordata'' can cause severe allergic reactions.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=21349062|year=2010|author1=Wang|first1=L|title=Adverse events to Houttuynia injection: A systematic review|journal=Journal of Evidence-Based Medicine|volume=3|issue=3|pages=168\u201376|last2=Cui|first2=X|last3=Cheng|first3=L|last4=Yuan|first4=Q|last5=Li|first5=T|last6=Li|first6=Y|last7=Deng|first7=S|last8=Shang|first8=H|last9=Bian|first9=Z|doi=10.1111/j.1756-5391.2010.01091.x}}</ref>\n\n== Aroma profile ==\nChemical compounds that contribute to the aroma of ''H. cordata'' include [[\u03b2-myrcene]]<ref name=vcca>{{cite journal\n |last            = Lu\n |first           = Hongmei\n |authorlink      = \n |title           = Variation in Chemical Composition and Antibacterial Activities of Essential Oils from Two Species of Houttuynia Thunb\n |journal         = [[Chemical & Pharmaceutical Bulletin]]\n |volume          = 54\n |issue           = 7\n |pages           = 936\u2013940\n |year            = 2006\n |url             = http://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cpb/54/7/936/_pdf\n |doi             = 10.1248/cpb.54.936\n |id              = \n |accessdate      = 31 March 2010\n |pmid            = 16819207\n |last2           = Wu\n |first2          = Xianjin\n |last3           = Liang\n |first3          = Yizeng\n |last4           = Zhang\n |first4          = Jian\n |display-authors = etal\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=gcmsa>{{cite journal\n |last            = Ch\n |first           = Muhammad Ishtiaq\n |authorlink      = \n |title           = Gas Chromatographic/Mass Spectrometric Analysis of the Essential Oil of Houttuynia cordata Thunb by Using On-Column Methylation with Tetramethylammonium Acetate\n |journal         = [[Journal of AOAC International]]\n |volume          = 90\n |issue           = 1\n |pages           = 60\u201367\n |year            = 2007\n |url             = http://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cpb/54/7/936/_pdf\n |doi             = \n |id              = \n |accessdate      = 31 March 2010\n |pmid            = 17373437\n |last2           = Wen\n |first2          = YF\n |last3           = Cheng\n |first3          = Y\n |display-authors = etal\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[2-Undecanone|2-undecanone]].<ref name=gcmsav>{{cite journal\n  | last = Liang\n  | first = Minmin\n  | authorlink =\n  | last2 = Qi\n  | first2 = M\n  | last3 = Zhang\n  | first3 = C\n  | last4 = Zhou\n  | first4 = S\n  | last5 = Fu\n  | first5 = R\n  | last6 = Huang\n  | first6 = J| title = Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry analysis of volatile compounds from Houttuynia cordata Thunb after extraction by solid-phase microextraction, flash evaporation and steam distillation\n  | journal = [[Analytica Chimica Acta]]\n  | volume = 531\n  | issue = 1\n  | pages = 97\u2013104\n  | year = 2005\n  | doi = 10.1016/j.aca.2004.09.082\n  | id =|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kampo herb list]]\n*[[Zhe'ergen]]\n*[[Sichuan cuisine]]\n*[[Yunnan cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Houttuynia cordata}}\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Houttuynia cordata}}\n*''Flora, The Gardener's Bible'', ABC Publishing, Ultimo, NSW, Australia, 2006 {{ISBN|0-7333-1439-2}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q164091}}\n\n[[Category:Saururaceae]]\n[[Category:Leaf vegetables]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional Chinese medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Houttuynia_cordata.jpg\n|genus = Houttuynia\n|species = cordata\n|authority = Thunb.\n}}\n\n'''''Houttuynia cordata''''', also known as '''fish mint''', '''fish leaf''', '''rainbow plant''', '''chameleon plant''', '''heart leaf''',  '''fish wort''', '''Chinese lizard tail''', or '''bishop's weed''', is one of two species in the genus ''[[Houttuynia]]'' (the other being ''H.&nbsp;emeiensis''). It is a [[flowering plant]] native to [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=\"rhs\">{{cite web|title=''Houttuynia cordata'', Thunb.|url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:927252-1|publisher=KewScience, The Royal Horticultural Society, UK|accessdate=8 October 2018|date=2018}}</ref> It grows in moist, shady locations.<ref name=\"pfaf\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pfaf.org/user/plant.aspx?latinname=Houttuynia+cordata |title=''Houttuynia cordata'' Thunb.|publisher=Plants for a Future|date=2012|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Growth==\n''Houttuynia cordata'' is a [[herbaceous]] [[perennial plant]] that can grow to {{convert|0.6|-|1|m|ft}}, spreading up to {{convert|1|m|ft}}.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> The proximal part of the stem is trailing and produces [[adventitious root]]s, while the distal part of the stem grows vertically. The [[Leaf|leaves]] are alternate, broadly heart-shaped, {{convert|4-9|cm|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|3-8|cm|abbr=on}} broad. Its [[flower]]s are greenish-yellow and borne on a terminal spike {{convert|2\u20133|cm|abbr=on}} long with four to six large white basal [[bract]]s.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> It normally blooms in the summer.\n\n==Cultivation==\n[[File:Houttuynia cordata Chameleon.jpg|thumb|right|''Houttuynia cordata'' 'Chameleon']]\n''Houttuynia cordata'' grows in moist to wet soil or slightly submerged in water, as long as it is exposed partially or fully to the sun.<ref name=pfaf/><ref name=rhs/> It can become invasive in gardens and difficult to eradicate. It propagates by division.\n\nIt is usually found in one of its cultivated forms in temperate gardens. The ''''Chameleon'''' variety (synonymous with ''H.cordata'' 'Court Jester',  'Tricolour', and 'Variegata') is slightly less vigorous than the parent species, with stubbier leaves mottled in both yellow and red. Another common variety, ''''Flore Pleno'''', has masses of white bracts and retains the vigor of the parent species.\n\n''Houttuynia cordata'' has been naturalized in North America.<ref>[http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?si=854 Global Invasive Species Database:  Houttuynia cordata], accessed 2008-07-06</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\n\n=== Culinary use ===\n[[File:Yakmomil-kkot-cha.jpg|thumb|Flowers picked for ''yakmomil-kkot-cha'' (flower tea) in ''[[sokuri]]'']]\nIt is commonly grown as a [[leaf vegetable]], and is used as a fresh herbal [[garnish (food)|garnish]].<ref name=pfaf/> The leaf has an unusual taste that is often described as 'fishy' (earning it the nickname \"fish mint\"), so it is not enjoyed as universally as basil, mint, or other more commonly used herbs.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn northeastern India, it is commonly used in salads or cooked with other vegetables, and as a garnish over side dishes.The tender roots can also be ground into chutneys along with dry fish, chilies, and tamarind. It is taken raw as salad and cooked along with fish as fish curry. In Japan and Korea, its dried leaves may be used as a tea.\n\nIn Vietnamese cuisine, it is called di\u1ebfp c\u00e1, and it is used with grilled meat and noodle salad dishes.<ref name=\"herbs\">[https://vietherbs.com/herb-directory/fish-herb/ Vietnamese Herbs: Fish Mint], Accessed October 9, 2018.</ref> Fish mint may be used as a garnish with several Vietnamese dishes, such as [[g\u1ecfi cu\u1ed1n]] stir-fried beef with fish mint salad,<ref>[https://www.sunset.com/food-wine/5-delicious-vietnamese-herbs-to-grow-and-eat Sunset: 5 Delicious Vietnamese Herbs to Grow and Eat], Accessed October 9, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://cookpad.com/vn/tim-kiem/rau%20di%E1%BA%BFp%20c%C3%A1 Cookpad, CookBook Inc.], Accessed October 9, 2018</ref> and [[b\u00e1nh x\u00e8o]].<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2011/10/18/141470565/banh-xeo-sizzling-crepes, NPR Inc.:Banh Xeo (Sizzling Crepes)], Accessed October 10, 2018</ref>\n\n====Zhe'ergen====\n[[File:Houttuynia_roots_vegetable_china.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Zhe'ergen is often served as a cold salad after being washed, diced and tossed with sauces derived from vinegar, chilli, coriander and soy sauce.]]\n'''Zh\u00e9'\u011brg\u0113n''' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u6298\u8033\u6839) is the edible rhizome of ''Houttuynia cordata'' ('''Yuxingcao''', \u9c7c\u8165\u8349 \u2018fish smelling leaf\u2019) with a fresh, spicy, peppery flavour that is used in southwestern Chinese cuisine, i.e. that of [[Guizhou]], [[Sichuan]], [[Yunnan]] and western [[Guangxi]]. Typically the leaves are eaten in Sichuan and the root in Guizhou. Zh\u00e9'\u011brg\u0113n fried with cured \u2018la rou\u2019 (a dried meat resembling \u2018Chinese bacon\u2019) is one of the staple dishes of Guizhou.\n\nNotable uses include:\n*part of the extensive [[fried rice]] cuisine of [[Guizhou]]\n*a condiment to ''[[migan (noodle)|migan]]'' and ''[[mixian (noodle)|mixian]]'' noodles when served in broth\n*as a component of dipping sauces used with the [[Shiping]] and [[Jianshui]] tradition of barbecued tofu\n*raw consumption as part of cold-tossed salads, when it is most frequently combined with [[coriander]], [[vinegar]], fresh [[Chili pepper|chilli]], and [[soy sauce]].\n\nThe leaves are also a little peppery and are frequently consumed in the region.\n\n=== Traditional medicine ===\n''Houttuynia cordata'' was used in [[traditional Chinese medicine]], including by Chinese scientists in an attempt to treat [[SARS]]<ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=18479853|year=2008|author1=Lau|first1=K. M|title=Immunomodulatory and anti-SARS activities of ''Houttuynia cordata''|journal=Journal of Ethnopharmacology|volume=118|issue=1|pages=79\u201385|last2=Lee|first2=K. M|last3=Koon|first3=C. M|last4=Cheung|first4=C. S|last5=Lau|first5=C. P|last6=Ho|first6=H. M|last7=Lee|first7=M. Y|last8=Au|first8=S. W|last9=Cheng|first9=C. H|last10=Lau|first10=C. B|last11=Tsui|first11=S. K|last12=Wan|first12=D. C|last13=Waye|first13=M. M|last14=Wong|first14=K. B|last15=Wong|first15=C. K|last16=Lam|first16=C. W|last17=Leung|first17=P. C|last18=Fung|first18=K. P|doi=10.1016/j.jep.2008.03.018}}</ref> and various other disorders,<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=3931198|year=2014|author1=Kumar|first1=M|title=A current update on the phytopharmacological aspects of ''Houttuynia cordata'' Thunb|journal=Pharmacognosy Reviews|volume=8|issue=15|pages=22\u201335|last2=Prasad|first2=S. K|last3=Hemalatha|first3=S|doi=10.4103/0973-7847.125525|pmid=24600193}}</ref> although there is no high-quality [[clinical research]] to confirm such uses are safe or effective, as of 2018. When administered via injection, ''H. cordata'' can cause severe allergic reactions.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=21349062|year=2010|author1=Wang|first1=L|title=Adverse events to Houttuynia injection: A systematic review|journal=Journal of Evidence-Based Medicine|volume=3|issue=3|pages=168\u201376|last2=Cui|first2=X|last3=Cheng|first3=L|last4=Yuan|first4=Q|last5=Li|first5=T|last6=Li|first6=Y|last7=Deng|first7=S|last8=Shang|first8=H|last9=Bian|first9=Z|doi=10.1111/j.1756-5391.2010.01091.x}}</ref>\n\n== Aroma profile ==\nChemical compounds that contribute to the aroma of ''H. cordata'' include [[\u03b2-myrcene]]<ref name=vcca>{{cite journal\n |last            = Lu\n |first           = Hongmei\n |authorlink      = \n |title           = Variation in Chemical Composition and Antibacterial Activities of Essential Oils from Two Species of Houttuynia Thunb\n |journal         = [[Chemical & Pharmaceutical Bulletin]]\n |volume          = 54\n |issue           = 7\n |pages           = 936\u2013940\n |year            = 2006\n |url             = http://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cpb/54/7/936/_pdf\n |doi             = 10.1248/cpb.54.936\n |id              = \n |accessdate      = 31 March 2010\n |pmid            = 16819207\n |last2           = Wu\n |first2          = Xianjin\n |last3           = Liang\n |first3          = Yizeng\n |last4           = Zhang\n |first4          = Jian\n |display-authors = etal\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=gcmsa>{{cite journal\n |last            = Ch\n |first           = Muhammad Ishtiaq\n |authorlink      = \n |title           = Gas Chromatographic/Mass Spectrometric Analysis of the Essential Oil of Houttuynia cordata Thunb by Using On-Column Methylation with Tetramethylammonium Acetate\n |journal         = [[Journal of AOAC International]]\n |volume          = 90\n |issue           = 1\n |pages           = 60\u201367\n |year            = 2007\n |url             = http://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cpb/54/7/936/_pdf\n |doi             = \n |id              = \n |accessdate      = 31 March 2010\n |pmid            = 17373437\n |last2           = Wen\n |first2          = YF\n |last3           = Cheng\n |first3          = Y\n |display-authors = etal\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[2-Undecanone|2-undecanone]].<ref name=gcmsav>{{cite journal\n  | last = Liang\n  | first = Minmin\n  | authorlink =\n  | last2 = Qi\n  | first2 = M\n  | last3 = Zhang\n  | first3 = C\n  | last4 = Zhou\n  | first4 = S\n  | last5 = Fu\n  | first5 = R\n  | last6 = Huang\n  | first6 = J| title = Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry analysis of volatile compounds from Houttuynia cordata Thunb after extraction by solid-phase microextraction, flash evaporation and steam distillation\n  | journal = [[Analytica Chimica Acta]]\n  | volume = 531\n  | issue = 1\n  | pages = 97\u2013104\n  | year = 2005\n  | doi = 10.1016/j.aca.2004.09.082\n  | id =|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kampo herb list]]\n*[[Zhe'ergen]]\n*[[Sichuan cuisine]]\n*[[Yunnan cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Houttuynia cordata}}\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Houttuynia cordata}}\n*''Flora, The Gardener's Bible'', ABC Publishing, Ultimo, NSW, Australia, 2006 {{ISBN|0-7333-1439-2}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q164091}}\n\n[[Category:Saururaceae]]\n[[Category:Leaf vegetables]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional Chinese medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Manjitrupbikram", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Houttuynia_cordata"}
{"title_page": "Lesser bamboo bat", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = Bates, P. | author2 = Francis, C. | author3 = Rosell-Ambal, G. | author4 = Heaney, L. | author5 = Molur, S. | author6 = Srinivasulu, C. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' | volume = 2008 | page = e.T22577A9377719 | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T22577A9377719.en }}</ref>\n| image = Lesser Bamboo Bat.JPG\n| genus = Tylonycteris\n| species = pachypus\n| authority = ([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1840)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''lesser bamboo bat''' or '''lesser flat-headed bat''' (''Tylonycteris pachypus'') is one of the smallest species of [[vesper bat]],<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|id=13802290}}</ref> and is native to Southeast Asia.\n\n==Description==\nThe bat, the size of a [[bumble bee]], is among the [[smallest organisms#Smallest mammal|smallest mammals]] on earth,<ref>[http://www.si.edu/Encyclopedia_si/nmnh/batfacts.htm Smithsonian Institution]</ref> measuring about {{convert|4|cm|abbr=on}} in head-body length with a tail about {{convert|2.5|cm|abbr=on}} long and a wingspan of {{convert|19|cm|abbr=on}}. Adults weigh between {{convert|1.4|and|5.2|g|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Eguren2014>{{cite journal |author1=Eguren, R.E.  |author2=McBee, K. | date = October 2014 | title = ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae)| journal = Mammalian Species | volume = 46 | issue = 910 | pages = 33\u201339 | doi = 10.1633/910}}</ref>\n\nThe fur ranges from golden or cinnamon to dark brown, and is paler on the underside of the body. The head is flattened, with a short snout and triangular ears with a wide [[tragus (ear)|tragus]].<ref name=Eguren2014/> The name ''pachypus'' means \"thick-footed\" and refers to the presence of smooth fleshy pads at the base of the thumb and on the heels of the feet, which help the bat grip onto bamboo stalks.<ref name=Medway1972>{{cite journal |author1=Medway, L.  |author2=Marshall A.G. | date = December 1972 | title = Roosting associations of flat-headed bats, ''Tylonycteris'' species (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Malaysia | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 168 | issue = 4 | pages = 463\u2013482 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.1972.tb01362.x}}</ref> The wings have an [[aspect ratio (aeronautics)|aspect ratio]] of 6.2, allowing the bat to be agile in flight at the expense of a slow speed.<ref name=Zhang2007>{{cite journal | author = Zhang, L. | date = March 2007 | title = Morphology, echolocation and foraging behaviour in two sympatric sibling species of bat (''Tylonycteris pachypus'' and ''Tylonycteris robustula'') (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 271 | issue = 3 | pages = 344\u2013351 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00210.x|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nA 4.8 gram T. pachypus has about an 80&nbsp;mg brain.<ref name=\"Pitnick2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Pitnick |first1=Scott |last2=Jones |first2=Kate E |last3=Wilkinson |first3=Gerald S |title=Mating system and brain size in bats |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=22 March 2006 |volume=273 |issue=1587 |at=Appendix 1: 719\u2013724 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2005.3367 |pmid=16608692|pmc=1560082 }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nLesser bamboo bats are found throughout [[Southeast Asia]] from [[Bangladesh]] to southern [[China]] and [[Indonesia]] and also in southern and eastern [[India]]. It inhabits deciduous forests with extensive areas of bamboo growth, at altitudes from sea level to {{convert|1260|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nFive subspecies are recognised:<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus aurex'' - India and Bangladesh\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus bhaktii'' - [[Lombok]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus fulvidus'' - China, [[Indochina]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus meyeri'' - [[Philippines]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus pachypus'' - Indonesia\n\n==Biology and behaviour==\n\nLesser bamboo bats typically roosts in the slit bored into the shoots of bamboo by [[leaf beetle]] larvae. The entrance slit to such cavities is too restrictive for most [[predator]]s, such as [[snake]]s, but the flattened head of the bamboo bat allows it to enter. Although the exact species vary across their range, in Malaysia, the preferred bamboo is ''[[Gigantochloa|Gigantochloa scortechinii]]'', and the beetles are most commonly ''[[Lasiochila goryi]]''. The bats sometimes use rock crevices or holes in trees as alternative roosting sites.<ref name=Medway1970>{{cite journal |author1=Medway, L.  |author2=Marshall, A.G. | date = August 1970 | title = Roost-site selection among flat-headed bats (''Tylonycteris'' spp.) | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 161 | issue = 2 | pages = 237\u2013245 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.1970.tb02038.x}}</ref> Females tend to roost in small groups of about five individuals, although larger groupings of up to 38 have been reported. Males roost alone, or in small groups of up to six.<ref name=Medway1970/><ref name=Hua2011>{{cite journal | author = Hua, P. | date = September 2011 | title = Hierarchical polygyny in multiparous lesser flat-headed bats | journal = Molecular Ecology | volume = 20 | issue = 17 | pages = 3669\u20133680 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-294X.2011.05192.x|display-authors=etal | pmid=21824210}}</ref> Individuals switch roosts every day, and larger groupings tend to be temporary.<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n\nThe bats are insectivorous, with flies, beetles, and [[hymenoptera]]ns forming the bulk of their diet.<ref name=Zhang2005>{{cite journal | author = [[:zh:\u5f20\u5229\u6807|Zhang, L.]] |date=September 2005 |title=Diet of Flat-Headed Bats, Tylonycteris pachypus and T. robustula, in Guangxi, South China | journal = Journal of Mammalogy | volume = 86 | issue = 1 | pages = 61\u201366 | doi = 10.1644/1545-1542(2005)086<0061:DOFBTP>2.0.CO;2|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref> They catch insects on the wing, using echolocation calls that start at 125&nbsp;kHz and drop to 50&nbsp;kHz.<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nLesser bamboo bats are [[polygyny|polygynous]], with females mating with multiple males throughout the September to November breeding season. Unusually for a tropical species, the females store the sperm after mating, with ovulation and fertilisation not occurring until January. Gestation lasts 12 to 13 weeks, with the young being born between April and May. Most births are of non-identical twins, although identical twins, singletons, and triplets are born on occasion.<ref name=Hua2011/><ref name=Medway1972b>{{cite journal | author = Medway, L. | date = February 1972 | title = Reproductive cycles of the flat-headed bats ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' and ''T. robustula'' (Chiroptera: Vespertilioninae) in a humid equatorial environment | journal = Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201361 | doi = 10.1111/j.1096-3642.1972.tb00772.x}}</ref>\n\nNewborn young are blind and hairless and weigh about {{convert|0.6|g|abbr=on}}. The mother carries her young for the first couple of days, but then leaves them behind in the bamboo chamber. The young are weaned and able to fly 22 to 25 days after birth. When their fur first begins to grow it is dark in colour, taking on the lighter and more reddish adult hue by October of their first year. Both males and females are sexually mature by the start of the first breeding season after birth.<ref name=Hua2011/><ref name=Medway1972b/>\n\n==Parasites==\n\n[[Bat flies]] which have the lesser bamboo bat as its [[host (biology)|host]] include ''[[Basilia brevipes]]'', ''[[Basilia majuscula]]'', and ''[[Basilia fletcheri]]''.<ref name=\"Theodor, 1956\">{{cite journal|last1=Theodor|first1=Oskar|title=On the genus ''Tripselia'' and the group of ''Basilia bathybothyra'' (Nycteribiidae, Diptera)|journal=Parasitology|date=1956|volume=46|issue=3-4|pages=353\u2013394|doi=10.1017/S003118200002655X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Wikispecies|Tylonycteris pachypus}}\n* {{NCBI|258959}}\n* {{ITIS|ID=632157}}\n* {{Eol|326346}}\n\n{{Vespertilionidae|V.|V.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q976615}}\n\n[[Category:Tylonycteris]]\n[[Category:Bats of Asia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bangladesh|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brunei]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Myanmar|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cambodia|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of China|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Timor|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Hong Kong|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of India|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Laos|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Philippines|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Pakistan|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Sri Lanka|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Thailand|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Taiwan|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of Asia|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1840]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = Bates, P. | author2 = Francis, C. | author3 = Rosell-Ambal, G. | author4 = Heaney, L. | author5 = Molur, S. | author6 = Srinivasulu, C. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' | volume = 2008 | page = e.T22577A9377719 | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T22577A9377719.en }}</ref>\n| image = Lesser Bamboo Bat.JPG\n| genus = Tylonycteris\n| species = pachypus\n| authority = ([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1840)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''lesser bamboo bat''' or '''lesser flat-headed bat''' (''Tylonycteris pachypus'') is one of the smallest species of [[vesper bat]],<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|id=13802290}}</ref> and is native to Southeast Asia.\n\n==Description==\nThe bat, the size of a [[bumble bee]], is among the [[smallest organisms#Smallest mammal|smallest mammals]] on earth,<ref>[http://www.si.edu/Encyclopedia_si/nmnh/batfacts.htm Smithsonian Institution]</ref> measuring about {{convert|4|cm|abbr=on}} in head-body length with a tail about {{convert|2.5|cm|abbr=on}} long and a wingspan of {{convert|19|cm|abbr=on}}. Adults weigh between {{convert|1.4|and|5.2|g|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Eguren2014>{{cite journal |author1=Eguren, R.E.  |author2=McBee, K. | date = October 2014 | title = ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae)| journal = Mammalian Species | volume = 46 | issue = 910 | pages = 33\u201339 | doi = 10.1633/910}}</ref>\n\nThe fur ranges from golden or cinnamon to dark brown, and is paler on the underside of the body. The head is flattened, with a short snout and triangular ears with a wide [[tragus (ear)|tragus]].<ref name=Eguren2014/> The name ''pachypus'' means \"thick-footed\" and refers to the presence of smooth fleshy pads at the base of the thumb and on the heels of the feet, which help the bat grip onto bamboo stalks.<ref name=Medway1972>{{cite journal |author1=Medway, L.  |author2=Marshall A.G. | date = December 1972 | title = Roosting associations of flat-headed bats, ''Tylonycteris'' species (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Malaysia | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 168 | issue = 4 | pages = 463\u2013482 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.1972.tb01362.x}}</ref> The wings have an [[aspect ratio (aeronautics)|aspect ratio]] of 6.2, allowing the bat to be agile in flight at the expense of a slow speed.<ref name=Zhang2007>{{cite journal | author = Zhang, L. | date = March 2007 | title = Morphology, echolocation and foraging behaviour in two sympatric sibling species of bat (''Tylonycteris pachypus'' and ''Tylonycteris robustula'') (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 271 | issue = 3 | pages = 344\u2013351 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00210.x|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nA 4.8 gram T. pachypus has about an 80&nbsp;mg brain.<ref name=\"Pitnick2006\">{{cite journal |last1=Pitnick |first1=Scott |last2=Jones |first2=Kate E |last3=Wilkinson |first3=Gerald S |title=Mating system and brain size in bats |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=22 March 2006 |volume=273 |issue=1587 |at=Appendix 1: 719\u2013724 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2005.3367 |pmid=16608692|pmc=1560082 }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nLesser bamboo bats are found throughout [[Southeast Asia]] from [[Bangladesh]] to southern [[China]] and [[Indonesia]] and also in southern and eastern [[India]]. It inhabits deciduous forests with extensive areas of bamboo growth, at altitudes from sea level to {{convert|1260|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nFive subspecies are recognised:<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus aurex'' - India and Bangladesh\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus bhaktii'' - [[Lombok]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus fulvidus'' - China, [[Indochina]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus meyeri'' - [[Philippines]]\n* ''Tylonycteris pachypus pachypus'' - Indonesia\n\n==Biology and behaviour==\n\nLesser bamboo bats typically roosts in the slit bored into the shoots of bamboo by [[leaf beetle]] larvae. The entrance slit to such cavities is too restrictive for most [[predator]]s, such as [[snake]]s, but the flattened head of the bamboo bat allows it to enter. Although the exact species vary across their range, in Malaysia, the preferred bamboo is ''[[Gigantochloa|Gigantochloa scortechinii]]'', and the beetles are most commonly ''[[Lasiochila goryi]]''. The bats sometimes use rock crevices or holes in trees as alternative roosting sites.<ref name=Medway1970>{{cite journal |author1=Medway, L.  |author2=Marshall, A.G. | date = August 1970 | title = Roost-site selection among flat-haded bats (''Tylonycteris'' spp.) | journal = Journal of Zoology | volume = 161 | issue = 2 | pages = 237\u2013245 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7998.1970.tb02038.x}}</ref> Females tend to roost in small groups of about five individuals, although larger groupings of up to 38 have been reported. Males roost alone, or in small groups of up to six.<ref name=Medway1970/><ref name=Hua2011>{{cite journal | author = Hua, P. | date = September 2011 | title = Hierarchical polygyny in multiparous lesser flat-headed bats | journal = Molecular Ecology | volume = 20 | issue = 17 | pages = 3669\u20133680 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-294X.2011.05192.x|display-authors=etal | pmid=21824210}}</ref> Individuals switch roosts every day, and larger groupings tend to be temporary.<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n\nThe bats are insectivorous, with flies, beetles, and [[hymenoptera]]ns forming the bulk of their diet.<ref name=Zhang2005>{{cite journal | author = [[:zh:\u5f20\u5229\u6807|Zhang, L.]] |date=September 2005 |title=Diet of Flat-Headed Bats, Tylonycteris pachypus and T. robustula, in Guangxi, South China | journal = Journal of Mammalogy | volume = 86 | issue = 1 | pages = 61\u201366 | doi = 10.1644/1545-1542(2005)086<0061:DOFBTP>2.0.CO;2|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref> They catch insects on the wing, using echolocation calls that start at 125&nbsp;kHz and drop to 50&nbsp;kHz.<ref name=Eguren2014/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nLesser bamboo bats are [[polygyny|polygynous]], with females mating with multiple males throughout the September to November breeding season. Unusually for a tropical species, the females store the sperm after mating, with ovulation and fertilisation not occurring until January. Gestation lasts 12 to 13 weeks, with the young being born between April and May. Most births are of non-identical twins, although identical twins, singletons, and triplets are born on occasion.<ref name=Hua2011/><ref name=Medway1972b>{{cite journal | author = Medway, L. | date = February 1972 | title = Reproductive cycles of the flat-headed bats ''Tylonycteris pachypus'' and ''T. robustula'' (Chiroptera: Vespertilioninae) in a humid equatorial environment | journal = Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201361 | doi = 10.1111/j.1096-3642.1972.tb00772.x}}</ref>\n\nNewborn young are blind and hairless and weigh about {{convert|0.6|g|abbr=on}}. The mother carries her young for the first couple of days, but then leaves them behind in the bamboo chamber. The young are weaned and able to fly 22 to 25 days after birth. When their fur first begins to grow it is dark in colour, taking on the lighter and more reddish adult hue by October of their first year. Both males and females are sexually mature by the start of the first breeding season after birth.<ref name=Hua2011/><ref name=Medway1972b/>\n\n==Parasites==\n\n[[Bat flies]] which have the lesser bamboo bat as its [[host (biology)|host]] include ''[[Basilia brevipes]]'', ''[[Basilia majuscula]]'', and ''[[Basilia fletcheri]]''.<ref name=\"Theodor, 1956\">{{cite journal|last1=Theodor|first1=Oskar|title=On the genus ''Tripselia'' and the group of ''Basilia bathybothyra'' (Nycteribiidae, Diptera)|journal=Parasitology|date=1956|volume=46|issue=3-4|pages=353\u2013394|doi=10.1017/S003118200002655X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Wikispecies|Tylonycteris pachypus}}\n* {{NCBI|258959}}\n* {{ITIS|ID=632157}}\n* {{Eol|326346}}\n\n{{Vespertilionidae|V.|V.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q976615}}\n\n[[Category:Tylonycteris]]\n[[Category:Bats of Asia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Bats of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bangladesh|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brunei]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Myanmar|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cambodia|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of China|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Timor|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Hong Kong|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of India|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Laos|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Philippines|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Pakistan|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Sri Lanka|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Thailand|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Taiwan|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of Asia|Bat, Lesser bamboo]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1840]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesser_bamboo_bat"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Qadiri", "text_new": "\n\n\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2011}} \n\n[[Image:Shrine Naushah Pak.jpg|thumb|The shrine of Sayyid Naushah Ganj Bakhsh at Ranmal Sharif,Tehsil Phalia (old district Gujrat) new district Mandi Bahauddin, Pakistan]]\n\n'''Syed Muhammad Nausha Ganj Bakhsh Qadiri''' (also spelled '''Qadri''', 21 August 1552 \u2013 18 May 1654), a scholar, saint and preacher of [[Islam]] in [[South Asia]] (today's [[Gujrat District|Gujrat]], [[Pakistan]]),<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071010081846/http://www.jamiyattablighulislam.org/</ref><ref>Abu Matlub Qadiri Naushahi ''Fayzan-e Naushah'' 2018 {{ISBN|978-94-92185-80-8}}</ref> was the founder of the [[Qadiriyya#Qadri_Noshahi|Naushahia]] branch of the [[Qadiriyya]] [[Sufi order]]. He preached in the tenth and eleventh centuries [[Islamic calendar|AH]] (sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries AD). His adherents call themselves Qadri Naushahi, Naushahi or just Qadri (Qadiri).\n\n== Birth and names ==\n\nSyed Muhammad Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri was born on the first day of Ramadan in 959 AH (21 August 1552) at Ghogganwali, district Gujrat in Punjab, Pakistan. The name of his father was Ala\u2019uddin, who was respected for being a great Sufi of his own times. Despite all difficulties of undertaking a long journey in his days he had completed his pilgrimage to Mecca Mukarramah and Madinah Munawwarah seven times on foot, which shows how devoted to Islam he was.\n\nAt his birth he was named (Haji) Muhammad. This name was kept in accordance with some divine and supernatural messages. In the first instance he became famous by the name of Haji Muhammad. Later on he also became famous by the names of Haji Nausha, Abul Hashim, Bhoora Wala Pir (the enshrouded one), Mujaddid-i Islam (the great revival of the Islam), Naushah Ganj Bakhsh, Syed Naushah Pir and Naushah Pak. The name Naushah is also spelled and pronounced as Noshah or even Nosho.\n\nAt his birth he was named Muhammad. Later on he also adopted the names Haji Naushah (Nosh\u0101h), Abul Hashim, Hazrat Naush\u0101h Wal\u012b, Bhoora Wala Pir (the enshrouded one), Mujaddid-i Azam (the great reviver of Islam), Naushah Ganj Bakhsh, Sayyid Naushah Pir and Naushah Pak. He claimed to have received the titles \"Ganj Bakhsh\" and \"Naushah\" in the presence of God. Both names are Persian words; Ganj Bakhsh means \"bestower of hidden treasures\" and Naushah means a young king or a bridegroom. He was also known as Maq\u0101m-i Naush\u0101hat.\n\n===Forebearers===\nMuhammad Qadri was a [[Sayyid]] (direct descendant of the family of [[Muhammad]]), a 33nd{{Clarify|date=July 2015|reason=Should this be '32nd', '33rd' or something else?}}-generation scion of [[Ali Ibn Abi Talib]].It has been recorded that the first of the ancestors of Syed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri, who came to the Indo-Pakistani subcontinent, was Syed Awn ibn Ya\u2018la, well known by the name of Qutb Shah Qadri. This happened by order of Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani in the fifth century AH (about the eleventh century AD). Moreover, he was an uncle of Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani and one of his spiritual successors born in 1028 in Baghdad. He is also the first person who introduced the Qadiria Order in India. Qutb Shah Qadiri was an appointed Qutb (spiritual pole) by Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani for this Indian subcontinent. Due to his great efforts many of the Hindu tribes converted to the Islam. Among them are the tribes of Rajput, Chohan and Khokar. Most of them attained a blessed life in the religion. Qutb Shah Qadiri returned after his mission, that he did for many years, to Baghdad where he died in 1157. In this city you can also find his holy grave.\n\nThe son and the spiritual successor of Qutb Shah Qadiri was Syed Zaman Ali Muhsin. He spread the Islam in the southwest regions of the Indo-Pakistani subcontinent, Kohistan-i Namak and the surroundings of Saunsakesar. Many people converted due to him to the Islam and joined in his circle of Murids (spiritual disciples). His work for the religion even impressed the local ruler \"Rani Bharat\", who later accepted the Islam as the true religion. The holy grave of Syed Zaman Ali Shah is located in Kirana, district Sargodha in Pakistan.\n\nSyed Mahmud Shah, better known as Pir Jalib, is one of the descendants of Syed Zaman Ali Shah. He was an outstanding saint who possessed super natural gifts, called Tasarrufat. He was also called Pir Jalib, because of his numerous benefactions and his spiritual attraction. Like his forefathers he was a spiritual perfected person. His holy burial place is in Ramdiana, district Sargodha. Syed Shamsuddin Shahid was a great saint from the descendants of Pir Jalib. He always took with him his favourite weapon, a javelin. Hence he was called Sangin Shah Shahid. He became a martyr when he died during a battle in the way of Allah. Sangin Shah had two sons: Syed Ala\u2019uddin Husain and Syed Rahimuddin. The holy graves of both the brothers are situated in Ghogganwali, near Qadirabad in the district Gujrat, Pakistan.\n\nSyed Ala\u2019uddin is reckoned among the great spiritual masters of the mystical path. He observed very accurately the Shair\u2018ah, the Islamic laws. He had the Kunyah (a nickname indicating a parental relationship) Abu Isma\u2018il with the extra appellation Pir Ghazi. Among his contemporaries, just as his younger brother, he was an exceptional saint, from whom supernatural powers have been revealed till today. Syed Ala\u2019uddin, whose holy grave is in Ghogganwali, is also the father of Syed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri <ref>http://www.qadri-naushahi.com/Resource/Nausha_Peer_RA.htm</ref>\n\n===Genealogy===\n\n{{div col | small=yes| colwidth=22em}}\n# [[Ali ibn Abu Talib]]\n# Abul Fadl Abbas\n# Abu Ali Ubaydullah\n# Abul Abbas Hasan\n# Abul Qasim Hamza\n# Jafar\n# Ali\n# Qasim\n# Muhammad al Tayar\n# Abu Yalla Hamza\n# Yalla Qasim\n# Aun Qutb Shah\n# Zaman Ali\n# Abdul Haqq\n# Jamaluddin Ishaq\n# Izzuddin Abdul Aziz\n# Jalaluddin Gohar Ali\n# Burhanuddin Hubaira\n# Saiduddin Iskander\n# Aminuddin Munawar\n# Jallaluddin Sultan\n# Kamaluddin Ahmad\n# Mahmud Shah\n# Abdul Awall Zahid\n# Ataullah\n# Abdul Samad Arif\n# Muizuddin\n# Ghulam Muhammad\n# Sahibuddin Shah\n# Abdullah Zakir e Hu\n# Jalaluddin Muhammad\n# Shamsuddin Ahmad\n# Alauddin Husayn\n# '''Muhammad Qadiri'''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Ministry and teaching==\nSyed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri was a saint of Allah by birth. He was highly gifted with the qualities of intelligence and memory. The books of religious history of his times tell us that he memorised the holy Qur'an within a short period of three months only. Among his teachers in this world were Qari Qaimuddin and Shaikh Abdul Haqq.\n\nHe was widely respected and honoured for his knowledge of Tasawwuf (Islamic mysticism), because his inner experience helped him to demonstrate his superiority in his field. Actually the knowledge infinitive mysticism came to him from Allah directly (Ilm-i Ladunni). Mirza Ahmed Beg Lahori records that one night two angels came and placed their fingers into the mouth of Syed Nausha. All of a sudden he became a learned and knowledgeable man in the field of Islamic mysticism. The next morning he told his teacher about this extraordinary spiritual experience. The teacher remarked: \"There is no need for you to get further knowledge from me. Perhaps on the Day of Judgement I shall be rewarded with salvation of my soul for having given a few lessons to you before this glorious spiritual experience.\"\n\nSyed Naushah Pir was an expert in the religious field, like Fiqh (Islamic law), Hadith (the report of the practise and sayings of the Prophet), Tafsir (exegeses of the Qur'an), logics, philosophy and Kalam (theology concerning the tenets of belief). His comprehensive knowledge of the religion is evident from his sayings.\n\nBeside the important languages such as Arabic and Persian he knew Kashmiri, Sanskrit and many another regional languages as well. After having Islamic knowledge, he specialized himself in spiritual exercises.\n\n== Golden Chain ==\nAt the age of twenty-nine years Muhammad accepted Hazrat Sakhi Shah Suleman Noori Hazoori (From Bhalwal Sharif) as his spiritual guide, placing him in a [[silsila]] (spiritual order or chain of saints) that stretched back to Abdul Qadir Jilani. This spiritual lineage ends via Ali Al-Murtaza at the final and Muhammad.<ref>(Tazkerah Naushahi copied 1190 AD Punjab University Library)</ref> {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\n{{div col | small=yes| colwidth=22em}}\n# [[Muhammad]]\n# [[Ali ibn Abu Talib]]\n# [[Hasan al-Basri]]\n# [[Habib al Ajami]]\n# [[Dawud Tai]]\n# [[Maruf Karkhi]]\n# [[Sirri Saqti]]\n# [[Junaid Baghdadi]]\n# [[Abu Bakr Shibli]]\n# [[Abdul Aziz bin Hars bin Asad Yemeni Tamimi|Abdul Aziz al Tamimi]]\n# [[Abu Al Fazal Abdul Wahid Yemeni Tamimi|Abul Fadl al Tamimi]]\n# [[Mohammad Yousaf Abu al-Farah Tartusi|Abul Farah Tartusi]]\n# [[Abul Hasan Hankari]]\n# [[Abu Saeed Mubarak Makhzoomi]]\n# [[Abdul Qadir Jilani]]\n# Syed Saifuddin Abdul Wahhab\n# Syed Safiuddin Abdus Sallam\n# Syed Hameeduddin Ahmad\n# Syed Muhiyuddin Mas`ud\n# Syed Ziauddin Ali\n# Syed Jamaluddin Shah Mir\n# Syed Shamsuddin A'zam\n# Syed Amiruddin Muhammad Ghawth\n# Syed Allauddin Mubarik Haqqani\n# Shaykh Maru`f Irfan\n# Shaykh Sulaiman Nuri\n# '''Muhammad Qadiri'''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Personal life ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2014}}\nHaji Muhammad was married to the daughter of Sayyid Abu Nasr Fateh Muhammad Shah of Qutb Naushehra. His mother, Main J\u012bwn\u012b, arranged this marriage. He had two sons and one daughter. Their names were Sayyid Muhammad Barkhurdar, Sayyid Muhammad Hashim and Sayyida Sairah Khatoon.\n\nHe was noted for his hospitality. Mirza Ahmed Beg Lahori states that he looked after his guests personally and arranged for their food himself. Allama Jam\u0101lullah says that once he and some of his pupils stayed in Sayyid Naushah's mosque. They were highly impressed when he sent food for them from his own house. It is on record that he directed his sons to look after the guests with special care, when he entrusted the work of preaching Islam to them.\n\nHe took part in many battles. It is recorded that once a renowned wrestler named Sher Ali Khan challenged Haji Muhammad to a trial of strength. Muhammad pressed Khan's hand so powerfully that blood came out of the wrestler's fingers. The wrestler fell down at his feet and begged to be forgiven.\n\nHe usually spent his time in the mosque in teaching the holy Qur'an, leading the prayers five times a day and leading additional Nafl prayers by the riverside in the night.\n\nHaji Muhammad attempted to put the [[Sunnah]] in practice as precisely as possible. He said: <blockquote>\"My way of life is the Shar\u012b'ah of the Prophet. My way of the Tar\u012bqah is the Shar\u012b'ah of the Prophet. The way of life of the Prophet implies also my way of life. To walk through the Shar\u012b'ah is like walking on an illuminated way.\"{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}</blockquote>\n\nBy day Muhammad always wore a big woollen sheet, as prescribed by the Sunnah. This piece of cloth is named bhoora in the Punjabi language, hence he was also called Bhoorawala Pir. Today, followers of his order also wear the bhoora.\n\n== Literary works ==\nThere are many works of Sayyid Naush\u0101h Ganj Bakhsh. As time passes they are compiled and published from manuscripts. At present there are five books of poetry and prose:\n*''Kulliy\u0101t-i Naush\u0101h'': ([[Urdu]] poetry) consisting of 76 Risala's and 2400 verses.\n*''Kulliy\u0101t-i Naush\u0101h'': ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] poetry) In this work 126 Risala's of about four thousand verses are alphabetically arranged.\n*''Ma\u2018\u0101rif-i Tasawwuf'': ([[Persian language|Persian]] poetry) dealing with assignments on the spiritual path.\n*''Maw\u0101'iz-i Naush\u0101h P\u012br'': (Punjabi prose) comprises delivered speeches and advices.\n*''Ganj-ul-Asr\u0101r'' (\"the treasure of mysteries\"): a short Risala in prose ascribed to him.\n\nAccording to Professor Ahmed Qureshi the following books are also written by Sayyid Naushah Pir: ''Diwan Urdu'', ''Diwan Punjabi'' (two poems in respectively Urdu and Punjabi) and ''Mathnawi-ye Ganj'' (\"The Mathnawi of Naushah Ganj Bakhsh\").\n\n==Quotations==\n\n\"O friend, withdraw yourself from the world.\"<br />\n\"If you don't, you have once to do that.\"<br />\n\"Don't spoil your time of life.\"<br />\n\"Leave the fame of the world behind you.\"<br />\n\"O my true friend, follow your Murshid (guide).\"<br />\n\"Do this in sincere surrendering in the heart with belief.\"<br />\n\"Commemorate the Kalima, so that you will not lose it.\"<br />\n\"The sufferings of this world and the last moment [death].\"<br />\n\"You can only prevail by this!\"\n\n== Death ==\nHaji Muhammad died of natural causes on Monday, the fifteenth of the Islamic month Rab\u012b 'ul-Awwal 1064 AH, aged one hundred and five. This date corresponds to Monday the eighteenth May 1654 A.D. He was buried in the village named Naushehra in Gujrat. His body was later interred at Ranmal Sharif in [[Gujrat city|Gujrat]]. His grave is open to the public. The part of land on which his grave has been buried, belongs to the territory of Ranmal Sharif. The number of plot was formerly 220 and at the present 84/1.\n\nDue to flooding in 1757 his body was transferred from its original burial site. According to tradition, when his coffin surfaced, his body was entirely intact, even his shroud was unharmed. After being damaged again by the river Chenab his coffin was finally moved to the west of Sahanpal Sharif. In 1950 this new tomb was damaged by rain. Consequently, the supports subsided and cracks appeared in the tomb. His death anniversary ('Urs) is held at this place every year again. Urs starts on 2nd Thursday of Har (Bikrami Calendar), which falls in the last 10 days of June and usually lasts 3 days. Thursday and Friday for men and Saturday for women.\n\n== Successors==\n\nA number of his sons and disciples carried his spiritual succession. In consequence, the Q\u0101dir\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b Order now includes many sub-branches carrying the name of his successors, such as Barkhurd\u0101r\u012b Naushah\u012b, H\u0101shim\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b, Suchy\u0101r\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b and Noushahi PAK REHMANI. For instance, the current head of the Naushahi Hashmi order is Shaykh Sayyid Mahroof Hussain Shah Naushahi Hashmi Qadiri, who founded the Sufi organisation [[Jamiyat Tabligh ul Islam]] in 1962 in the United Kingdom.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.qadri-naushahi.com/\n*https://archive.org/details/FAYZANENAUSHAHSecondEdition \u2013 Biographies of the spiritual masters and saints of the Q\u0101diriyah Naush\u0101hiyah Order\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071010081846/http://www.jamiyattablighulislam.org/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070929071637/http://www.naushahi.co.uk/Generations/ \u2013 Up-to-date Family Tree of Muhammad Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri\n\n{{Sufism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qadiri, Muhammad}}\n[[Category:Phalia]]\n[[Category:1552 births]]\n[[Category:1654 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Arab descent]]\n[[Category:Mughal Empire Sufis]]\n[[Category:Qadiri order]]\n[[Category:Punjabi Sufi saints]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2011}} \n\n[[Image:Shrine Naushah Pak.jpg|thumb|The shrine of Sayyid Naushah Ganj Bakhsh at Ranmal Sharif,Tehsil Phalia (old district Gujrat) new district Mandi Bahauddin, Pakistan]]\n\n'''Syed Muhammad Nausha Ganj Bakhsh Qadiri''' (also spelled '''Qadri''', 21 August 1552 \u2013 18 May 1654), a scholar, saint and preacher of [[Islam]] in [[South Asia]] (today's [[Gujrat District|Gujrat]], [[Pakistan]]),<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20071010081846/http://www.jamiyattablighulislam.org/</ref><ref>Abu Matlub Qadiri Naushahi ''Fayzan-e Naushah'' 2018 {{ISBN|978-94-92185-80-8}}</ref> was the founder of the [[Qadiriyya#Qadri_Noshahi|Naushahia]] branch of the [[Qadiriyya]] [[Sufi order]]. He preached in the tenth and eleventh centuries [[Islamic calendar|AH]] (sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries AD). His adherents call themselves Qadri Naushahi, Naushahi or just Qadri (Qadiri).\n\n== Birth and names ==\n\nSyed Muhammad Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri was born on the first day of Ramadan in 959 AH (21 August 1552) at Ghogganwali, district Gujrat in Punjab, Pakistan. The name of his father was Ala\u2019uddin, who was respected for being a great Sufi of his own times. Despite all difficulties of undertaking a long journey in his days he had completed his pilgrimage to Mecca Mukarramah and Madinah Munawwarah seven times on foot, which shows how devoted to Islam he was.\n\nAt his birth he was named (Haji) Muhammad. This name was kept in accordance with some divine and supernatural messages. In the first instance he became famous by the name of Haji Muhammad. Later on he also became famous by the names of Haji Nausha, Abul Hashim, Bhoora Wala Pir (the enshrouded one), Mujaddid-i Islam (the great revival of the Islam), Naushah Ganj Bakhsh, Syed Naushah Pir and Naushah Pak. The name Naushah is also spelled and pronounced as Noshah or even Nosho.\n\nAt his birth he was named Muhammad. Later on he also adopted the names Haji Naushah (Nosh\u0101h), Abul Hashim, Hazrat Naush\u0101h Wal\u012b, Bhoora Wala Pir (the enshrouded one), Mujaddid-i Azam (the great reviver of Islam), Naushah Ganj Bakhsh, Sayyid Naushah Pir and Naushah Pak. He claimed to have received the titles \"Ganj Bakhsh\" and \"Naushah\" in the presence of God. Both names are Persian words; Ganj Bakhsh means \"bestower of hidden treasures\" and Naushah means a young king or a bridegroom. He was also known as Maq\u0101m-i Naush\u0101hat.\n\n===Forebearers===\nMuhammad Qadri was a [[Sayyid]] (direct descendant of the family of [[Muhammad]]), a 33nd{{Clarify|date=July 2015|reason=Should this be '32nd', '33rd' or something else?}}-generation scion of [[Ali Ibn Abi Talib]].It has been recorded that the first of the ancestors of Syed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri, who came to the Indo-Pakistani subcontinent, was Syed Awn ibn Ya\u2018la, well known by the name of Qutb Shah Qadri. This happened by order of Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani in the fifth century AH (about the eleventh century AD). Moreover, he was an uncle of Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani and one of his spiritual successors born in 1028 in Baghdad. He is also the first person who introduced the Qadiria Order in India. Qutb Shah Qadiri was an appointed Qutb (spiritual pole) by Syed Abdul Qadir Jilani for this Indian subcontinent. Due to his great efforts many of the Hindu tribes converted to the Islam. Among them are the tribes of Rajput, Chohan and Khokar. Most of them attained a blessed life in the religion. Qutb Shah Qadiri returned after his mission, that he did for many years, to Baghdad where he died in 1157. In this city you can also find his holy grave.\n\nThe son and the spiritual successor of Qutb Shah Qadiri was Syed Zaman Ali Muhsin. He spread the Islam in the southwest regions of the Indo-Pakistani subcontinent, Kohistan-i Namak and the surroundings of Saunsakesar. Many people converted due to him to the Islam and joined in his circle of Murids (spiritual disciples). His work for the religion even impressed the local ruler \"Rani Bharat\", who later accepted the Islam as the true religion. The holy grave of Syed Zaman Ali Shah is located in Kirana, district Sargodha in Pakistan.\n\nSyed Mahmud Shah, better known as Pir Jalib, is one of the descendants of Syed Zaman Ali Shah. He was an outstanding saint who possessed super natural gifts, called Tasarrufat. He was also called Pir Jalib, because of his numerous benefactions and his spiritual attraction. Like his forefathers he was a spiritual perfected person. His holy burial place is in Ramdiana, district Sargodha. Syed Shamsuddin Shahid was a great saint from the descendants of Pir Jalib. He always took with him his favourite weapon, a javelin. Hence he was called Sangin Shah Shahid. He became a martyr when he died during a battle in the way of Allah. Sangin Shah had two sons: Syed Ala\u2019uddin Husain and Syed Rahimuddin. The holy graves of both the brothers are situated in Ghogganwali, near Qadirabad in the district Gujrat, Pakistan.\n\nSyed Ala\u2019uddin is reckoned among the great spiritual masters of the mystical path. He observed very accurately the Shair\u2018ah, the Islamic laws. He had the Kunyah (a nickname indicating a parental relationship) Abu Isma\u2018il with the extra appellation Pir Ghazi. Among his contemporaries, just as his younger brother, he was an exceptional saint, from whom supernatural powers have been revealed till today. Syed Ala\u2019uddin, whose holy grave is in Ghogganwali, is also the father of Syed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri <ref>http://www.qadri-naushahi.com/Resource/Nausha_Peer_RA.htm</ref>\n\n===Genealogy===\n\n{{div col | small=yes| colwidth=22em}}\n# [[Ali ibn Abu Talib]]\n# Abul Fadl Abbas\n# Abu Ali Ubaydullah\n# Abul Abbas Hasan\n# Abul Qasim Hamza\n# Jafar\n# Ali\n# Qasim\n# Muhammad al Tayar\n# Abu Yalla Hamza\n# Yalla Qasim\n# Aun Qutb Shah\n# Zaman Ali\n# Abdul Haqq\n# Jamaluddin Ishaq\n# Izzuddin Abdul Aziz\n# Jalaluddin Gohar Ali\n# Burhanuddin Hubaira\n# Saiduddin Iskander\n# Aminuddin Munawar\n# Jallaluddin Sultan\n# Kamaluddin Ahmad\n# Mahmud Shah\n# Abdul Awall Zahid\n# Ataullah\n# Abdul Samad Arif\n# Muizuddin\n# Ghulam Muhammad\n# Sahibuddin Shah\n# Abdullah Zakir e Hu\n# Jalaluddin Muhammad\n# Shamsuddin Ahmad\n# Alauddin Husayn\n# '''Muhammad Qadiri'''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Ministry and teaching==\nSyed Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri was a saint of Allah by birth. He was highly gifted with the qualities of intelligence and memory. The books of religious history of his times tell us that he memorised the holy Qur'an within a short period of three months only. Among his teachers in this world were Qari Qaimuddin and Shaikh Abdul Haqq.\n\nHe was widely respected and honoured for his knowledge of Tasawwuf (Islamic mysticism), because his inner experience helped him to demonstrate his superiority in his field. Actually the knowledge infinitive mysticism came to him from Allah directly (Ilm-i Ladunni). Mirza Ahmed Beg Lahori records that one night two angels came and placed their fingers into the mouth of Syed Nausha. All of a sudden he became a learned and knowledgeable man in the field of Islamic mysticism. The next morning he told his teacher about this extraordinary spiritual experience. The teacher remarked: \"There is no need for you to get further knowledge from me. Perhaps on the Day of Judgement I shall be rewarded with salvation of my soul for having given a few lessons to you before this glorious spiritual experience.\"\n\nSyed Naushah Pir was an expert in the religious field, like Fiqh (Islamic law), Hadith (the report of the practise and sayings of the Prophet), Tafsir (exegeses of the Qur'an), logics, philosophy and Kalam (theology concerning the tenets of belief). His comprehensive knowledge of the religion is evident from his sayings.\n\nBeside the important languages such as Arabic and Persian he knew Kashmiri, Sanskrit and many another regional languages as well. After having Islamic knowledge, he specialized himself in spiritual exercises.\n\n== Golden Chain ==\nAt the age of twenty-nine years Muhammad accepted Shah Sulaim\u0101n N\u016bri as his spiritual guide, placing him in a [[silsila]] (spiritual order or chain of saints) that stretched back to Abdul Qadir Jilani. This spiritual lineage ends via Ali Al-Murtaza at the final and Muhammad.<ref>(Tazkerah Naushahi copied 1190 AD Punjab University Library)</ref> {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\n{{div col | small=yes| colwidth=22em}}\n# [[Muhammad]]\n# [[Ali ibn Abu Talib]]\n# [[Hasan al-Basri]]\n# [[Habib al Ajami]]\n# [[Dawud Tai]]\n# [[Maruf Karkhi]]\n# [[Sirri Saqti]]\n# [[Junaid Baghdadi]]\n# [[Abu Bakr Shibli]]\n# [[Abdul Aziz bin Hars bin Asad Yemeni Tamimi|Abdul Aziz al Tamimi]]\n# [[Abu Al Fazal Abdul Wahid Yemeni Tamimi|Abul Fadl al Tamimi]]\n# [[Mohammad Yousaf Abu al-Farah Tartusi|Abul Farah Tartusi]]\n# [[Abul Hasan Hankari]]\n# [[Abu Saeed Mubarak Makhzoomi]]\n# [[Abdul Qadir Jilani]]\n# Syed Saifuddin Abdul Wahhab\n# Syed Safiuddin Abdus Sallam\n# Syed Hameeduddin Ahmad\n# Syed Muhiyuddin Mas`ud\n# Syed Ziauddin Ali\n# Syed Jamaluddin Shah Mir\n# Syed Shamsuddin A'zam\n# Syed Amiruddin Muhammad Ghawth\n# Syed Allauddin Mubarik Haqqani\n# Shaykh Maru`f Irfan\n# Shaykh Sulaiman Nuri\n# '''Muhammad Qadiri'''\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Personal life ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2014}}\nHaji Muhammad was married to the daughter of Sayyid Abu Nasr Fateh Muhammad Shah of Qutb Naushehra. His mother, Main J\u012bwn\u012b, arranged this marriage. He had two sons and one daughter. Their names were Sayyid Muhammad Barkhurdar, Sayyid Muhammad Hashim and Sayyida Sairah Khatoon.\n\nHe was noted for his hospitality. Mirza Ahmed Beg Lahori states that he looked after his guests personally and arranged for their food himself. Allama Jam\u0101lullah says that once he and some of his pupils stayed in Sayyid Naushah's mosque. They were highly impressed when he sent food for them from his own house. It is on record that he directed his sons to look after the guests with special care, when he entrusted the work of preaching Islam to them.\n\nHe took part in many battles. It is recorded that once a renowned wrestler named Sher Ali Khan challenged Haji Muhammad to a trial of strength. Muhammad pressed Khan's hand so powerfully that blood came out of the wrestler's fingers. The wrestler fell down at his feet and begged to be forgiven.\n\nHe usually spent his time in the mosque in teaching the holy Qur'an, leading the prayers five times a day and leading additional Nafl prayers by the riverside in the night.\n\nHaji Muhammad attempted to put the [[Sunnah]] in practice as precisely as possible. He said: <blockquote>\"My way of life is the Shar\u012b'ah of the Prophet. My way of the Tar\u012bqah is the Shar\u012b'ah of the Prophet. The way of life of the Prophet implies also my way of life. To walk through the Shar\u012b'ah is like walking on an illuminated way.\"{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}</blockquote>\n\nBy day Muhammad always wore a big woollen sheet, as prescribed by the Sunnah. This piece of cloth is named bhoora in the Punjabi language, hence he was also called Bhoorawala Pir. Today, followers of his order also wear the bhoora.\n\n== Literary works ==\nThere are many works of Sayyid Naush\u0101h Ganj Bakhsh. As time passes they are compiled and published from manuscripts. At present there are five books of poetry and prose:\n*''Kulliy\u0101t-i Naush\u0101h'': ([[Urdu]] poetry) consisting of 76 Risala's and 2400 verses.\n*''Kulliy\u0101t-i Naush\u0101h'': ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] poetry) In this work 126 Risala's of about four thousand verses are alphabetically arranged.\n*''Ma\u2018\u0101rif-i Tasawwuf'': ([[Persian language|Persian]] poetry) dealing with assignments on the spiritual path.\n*''Maw\u0101'iz-i Naush\u0101h P\u012br'': (Punjabi prose) comprises delivered speeches and advices.\n*''Ganj-ul-Asr\u0101r'' (\"the treasure of mysteries\"): a short Risala in prose ascribed to him.\n\nAccording to Professor Ahmed Qureshi the following books are also written by Sayyid Naushah Pir: ''Diwan Urdu'', ''Diwan Punjabi'' (two poems in respectively Urdu and Punjabi) and ''Mathnawi-ye Ganj'' (\"The Mathnawi of Naushah Ganj Bakhsh\").\n\n==Quotations==\n\n\"O friend, withdraw yourself from the world.\"<br />\n\"If you don't, you have once to do that.\"<br />\n\"Don't spoil your time of life.\"<br />\n\"Leave the fame of the world behind you.\"<br />\n\"O my true friend, follow your Murshid (guide).\"<br />\n\"Do this in sincere surrendering in the heart with belief.\"<br />\n\"Commemorate the Kalima, so that you will not lose it.\"<br />\n\"The sufferings of this world and the last moment [death].\"<br />\n\"You can only prevail by this!\"\n\n== Death ==\nHaji Muhammad died of natural causes on Monday, the fifteenth of the Islamic month Rab\u012b 'ul-Awwal 1064 AH, aged one hundred and five. This date corresponds to Monday the eighteenth May 1654 A.D. He was buried in the village named Naushehra in Gujrat. His body was later interred at Ranmal Sharif in [[Gujrat city|Gujrat]]. His grave is open to the public. The part of land on which his grave has been buried, belongs to the territory of Ranmal Sharif. The number of plot was formerly 220 and at the present 84/1.\n\nDue to flooding in 1757 his body was transferred from its original burial site. According to tradition, when his coffin surfaced, his body was entirely intact, even his shroud was unharmed. After being damaged again by the river Chenab his coffin was finally moved to the west of Sahanpal Sharif. In 1950 this new tomb was damaged by rain. Consequently, the supports subsided and cracks appeared in the tomb. His death anniversary ('Urs) is held at this place every year again. Urs starts on 2nd Thursday of Har (Bikrami Calendar), which falls in the last 10 days of June and usually lasts 3 days. Thursday and Friday for men and Saturday for women.\n\n== Successors==\n\nA number of his sons and disciples carried his spiritual succession. In consequence, the Q\u0101dir\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b Order now includes many sub-branches carrying the name of his successors, such as Barkhurd\u0101r\u012b Naushah\u012b, H\u0101shim\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b, Suchy\u0101r\u012b Naush\u0101h\u012b and Noushahi PAK REHMANI. For instance, the current head of the Naushahi Hashmi order is Shaykh Sayyid Mahroof Hussain Shah Naushahi Hashmi Qadiri, who founded the Sufi organisation [[Jamiyat Tabligh ul Islam]] in 1962 in the United Kingdom.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.qadri-naushahi.com/\n*https://archive.org/details/FAYZANENAUSHAHSecondEdition \u2013 Biographies of the spiritual masters and saints of the Q\u0101diriyah Naush\u0101hiyah Order\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071010081846/http://www.jamiyattablighulislam.org/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070929071637/http://www.naushahi.co.uk/Generations/ \u2013 Up-to-date Family Tree of Muhammad Naushah Ganj Bakhsh Qadri\n\n{{Sufism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qadiri, Muhammad}}\n[[Category:Phalia]]\n[[Category:1552 births]]\n[[Category:1654 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Arab descent]]\n[[Category:Mughal Empire Sufis]]\n[[Category:Qadiri order]]\n[[Category:Punjabi Sufi saints]]\n", "name_user": "Saadulhassan2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_Qadiri"}
{"title_page": "Mthuli Ncube", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Mthuli Ncube\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| school_tradition = \n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| office      = [[List of Finance Ministers of Zimbabwe|Minister for Finance & Economic Development]]\n| term_start  = 10 September 2018\n| term_end    = \n| president   = [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]]\n| predecessor = [[Patrick Chinamasa]]\n| successor   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|30 November 1964}}\n| birth_place = Bulawayo\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = Zimbabwean\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| influences  = \n| influenced  =  \n| awards      =\n| memorials   = \n| spouse      =\n| signature   = <!--(filename only)-->\n| module      = \n}}\n\n'''Mthuli Ncube''' (born 30 November 1964),<ref name=\"Birth\">The journal ''Africa Confidential'' lists his birth date as 30 November 1964 {{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/3241/Mthuli_Ncube |accessdate= 5 March 2020 }}; although the entry at {{Cite web| title= Ncube, Mthuli, 1963- | url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2013034158.html | publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 28 September 2014 }} uses 1963.</ref> is the minister of Finance in the Zimbabwe cabinet appointed by president [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]]<ref name=\"Dzirutwe\">{{Cite news|last=Dzirutwe |first=MacDonald |date=7 September 2018 |title=Zimbabwe's Mnangagwa names ex-banker Mthuli Ncube finance minister |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zimbabwe-politics/zimbabwe-mnangagwa-names-former-banker-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister-idUSKCN1LN1NW |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908135202/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zimbabwe-politics/zimbabwe-mnangagwa-names-former-banker-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister-idUSKCN1LN1NW |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref> and past [[chief economist]] and [[Vice President]] of the [[African Development Bank]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Sweden's H&M Sets Sail For Africa |last=Clark |first=Meagan |date=15 January 2014 |newspaper=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/swedens-hm-sets-sail-africa-1540654 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122031632/http://www.ibtimes.com/swedens-hm-sets-sail-africa-1540654|archive-date=22 January 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Africa\u2019s Middle Class Spearheads Economic Growth |date=26 December 2013 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] |url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/survey/so/2013/INT122613A.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105033838/http://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2015/09/28/04/53/soint122613a |archive-date=5 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy}}</ref> He holds a PhD in [[Mathematical Finance]] from [[Cambridge University]]. On 7 September 2018, President [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] announced Zimbabwe's new cabinet where he named Professor Mthuli Ncube as the Finance Minister.<ref name=\"Banda\">{{Cite magazine|title=Mnangagwa names #ZimCabinet, appoints African Development Bank Vice President Prof Mthuli Ncube as Finance Minister |magazine=Celeb Gossip News |date=7 September 2018 |url=https://www.celebgossip.co.za/international-news/5148-mnangagwa-names-zimcabinet-appoints-african-development-bank-vice-president-prof-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907183125/https://www.celebgossip.co.za/international-news/5148-mnangagwa-names-zimcabinet-appoints-african-development-bank-vice-president-prof-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister.html |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nBefore joining the bank, he was dean and professor of finance at [[Wits Business School]] and then dean of the faculty of Commerce, Law and Management at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] (Wits) as well as a lecturer in finance at the [[London School of Economics]].\n\nHe has published a number of award-winning papers{{Citation needed|reason=What awards?|date=January 2019}} in the area of finance and economics as well as a number of books including, ''Mathematical Finance: Option and Asset Pricing'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=2010 |title=Mathematical Finance: Option and Asset Pricing |location=Sandton, Johannesburg, South Africa |publisher=Heinemann |isbn=978-0-7962-3386-8}}, no reviews found.</ref> ''South African Dictionary of Finance'' (editor);<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wuite |first=Rudy |year=2009 |editor-last=Ncube |editor-first=Mthuli |title=South African Dictionary of Finance |location=Northcliff, South Africa |publisher=Rollerbird Press |isbn=978-1-920334-02-4}}</ref> ''Financial Systems and Monetary Policy in Africa'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=2008 |title=Financial Systems and Monetary Policy in Africa |location=Nairobi, Kenya |publisher=African Economic Research Consortium |isbn=978-9966-778-30-7}}, no reviews found.</ref> ''Development Dynamics: Theories and Lessons from Zimbabwe'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=1991 |title=Development Dynamics: Theories and Lessons from Zimbabwe |location= Aldershot, Haunts, England |publisher=Avebury |isbn=978-1-85628-087-7}}, no reviews found.</ref> and ''Monetary Policy and the Economy in South Africa'' (with Eliphas Ndou).<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Ncube |first1=Mthuli |last2=Ndou |first2=Eliphas |year=2013 |title=Monetary Policy and the Economy in South Africa |location=London |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-137-33414-5}}</ref>\n\nNcube is currently a visiting professor at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"Oxford\">{{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube, visiting professor 2017\u20132020 |publisher=University of Oxford |url=https://www.bsg.ox.ac.uk/people/mthuli-ncube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029025413/https://www.bsg.ox.ac.uk/people/mthuli-ncube |archive-date=29 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n==Work at the African Development Bank==\nNcube was the Chief Economist and Vice President of the [[African Development Bank]] (AfDB).<ref name=\"Oxford\" /> As Chief Economist, he oversaw the Economics Complex, which is focused on the process of knowledge management within the Bank and with its partners, and general strategic economic research within the Bank. In this regard, he supervised the Development Research Department, Statistics Department and African Development Institute. As a Vice President, Professor Mthuli Ncube was a member of the senior management team of the Bank and contributed to its general strategic direction.<ref name=\"Banda\" />\n\n==Other work==\nNcube was also a regulator and a board member of the [[South African Financial Services Board]] (FSB), which regulates non-bank financial institutions in South Africa, founding  chairman of [[Barbican and Selwyn Capital]] and worked for [[Investec]] Asset Management as a Portfolio Manager and Head of Asset Allocation Strategy.<ref name=\"Oxford\" />\n\nNcube has also been Chairman of the Board of the [[African Economic Research Consortium]],<ref name=\"Vibrant-Bio\">{{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube, Vice President and Chief Economist |date=2012 |work=Distinguished Lecture Series |publisher=Vibrant Media |location=Johannesburg, South Africa |url=http://www.vibrantmedia.co.za/m/wbs/12/DistinguishedLectureSeries/DLS_MthuliNcube/bio.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109044039/http://www.vibrantmedia.co.za/m/wbs/12/DistinguishedLectureSeries/DLS_MthuliNcube/bio.pdf |archive-date=9 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> chairman of the Global Agenda Council on \"Poverty and Economic Development\" ([[World Economic Forum]]) and a governor of the [[African Capacity Building Foundation]].{{fact|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Finance Minister==\nNcube was appointed Minister of Finance in Zimbabwe on Friday 7 September 2018 under President Emmerson Mnangagwa's government.<ref name=\"Dzirutwe\" /><ref name=\"Banda\" />  In 2019, he presided over the conversion from foreign currency to a [[RTGS dollar|new Zimbabwean currency]], and the resultant return of [[Hyperinflation in Zimbabwe|hyper-inflation]].<ref name=\"Mordasov\">{{Cite news|last=Mordasov |first=Pavel |date=9 October 2019 |title=The Return of Hyperinflation in Zimbabwe |newspaper=Mises Wire |publisher=Mises Institute |location=Auburn, Alabama |url=https://mises.org/wire/return-hyperinflation-zimbabwe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011051941/https://mises.org/wire/return-hyperinflation-zimbabwe |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Amin\">{{Cite news|last=Amin |first=Haslinda |title=At More Than 500%, Zimbabwe\u2019s Ncube Sees Inflation Stabilizing |date=22 January 2020 |newspaper=Bloomberg News |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/at-more-than-500-zimbabwe-s-ncube-sees-inflation-stabilizing |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226133208/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/at-more-than-500-zimbabwe-s-ncube-sees-inflation-stabilizing |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vinga |first=Alois |date=26 January 2020 |title=Ncube scorned for Davos claims Zim economy recovering |newspaper=New Zimbabwe |url=https://www.newzimbabwe.com/ncube-scorned-for-davos-claims-zim-economy-recovering/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126101330/https://www.newzimbabwe.com/ncube-scorned-for-davos-claims-zim-economy-recovering/ |archive-date=26 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Ncube suspended publishing inflation data after June 2019,<ref name=\"Amin\"/> and in October 2019 he indicated inflation figures for Zimbabwe would again be released in February 2020.<ref name=\"Mordasov\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nNcube is married and has four children.<ref name=\"Vibrant-Bio\" /> and has failed the Zimbabwean people terribly. He boasts a great number of titles under his academic belt however all his accolades have done little to improve the economy of the country. Since being called in to rescue the crippled economy of Zimbabwe, he has been preoccupied with how he looks on camera and brought ineffective changes to the bread and butter issues. He has not acknowledged his failure, and has proven to be about as useful as a chocolate teapot. Meanwhile the people of the country continue to  struggle and wallow in abject poverty.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.afdb.org/en/knowledge/economics-research/our-researchers/mthuli-ncube/ Profile at the African Development Bank]\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ncube, Mthuli}}\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand academics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:South African economists]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Mthuli Ncube\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| school_tradition = \n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| office      = [[List of Finance Ministers of Zimbabwe|Minister for Finance & Economic Development]]\n| term_start  = 10 September 2018\n| term_end    = \n| president   = [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]]\n| predecessor = [[Patrick Chinamasa]]\n| successor   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|30 November 1964}}\n| birth_place = Bulawayo\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = Zimbabwean\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| influences  = \n| influenced  =  \n| awards      =\n| memorials   = \n| spouse      =\n| signature   = <!--(filename only)-->\n| module      = \n}}\n\n'''Mthuli Ncube''' (born 30 November 1964),<ref name=\"Birth\">The journal ''Africa Confidential'' lists his birth date as 30 November 1964 {{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/3241/Mthuli_Ncube |accessdate= 5 March 2020 }}; although the entry at {{Cite web| title= Ncube, Mthuli, 1963- | url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2013034158.html | publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 28 September 2014 }} uses 1963.</ref> is the minister of Finance in the Zimbabwe cabinet appointed by president [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]]<ref name=\"Dzirutwe\">{{Cite news|last=Dzirutwe |first=MacDonald |date=7 September 2018 |title=Zimbabwe's Mnangagwa names ex-banker Mthuli Ncube finance minister |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zimbabwe-politics/zimbabwe-mnangagwa-names-former-banker-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister-idUSKCN1LN1NW |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908135202/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-zimbabwe-politics/zimbabwe-mnangagwa-names-former-banker-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister-idUSKCN1LN1NW |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref> and past [[chief economist]] and [[Vice President]] of the [[African Development Bank]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Sweden's H&M Sets Sail For Africa |last=Clark |first=Meagan |date=15 January 2014 |newspaper=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/swedens-hm-sets-sail-africa-1540654 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122031632/http://www.ibtimes.com/swedens-hm-sets-sail-africa-1540654|archive-date=22 January 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Africa\u2019s Middle Class Spearheads Economic Growth |date=26 December 2013 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] |url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/survey/so/2013/INT122613A.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105033838/http://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2015/09/28/04/53/soint122613a |archive-date=5 January 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy}}</ref> He holds a PhD in [[Mathematical Finance]] from [[Cambridge University]]. On 7 September 2018, President [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] announced Zimbabwe's new cabinet where he named Professor Mthuli Ncube as the Finance Minister.<ref name=\"Banda\">{{Cite magazine|title=Mnangagwa names #ZimCabinet, appoints African Development Bank Vice President Prof Mthuli Ncube as Finance Minister |magazine=Celeb Gossip News |date=7 September 2018 |url=https://www.celebgossip.co.za/international-news/5148-mnangagwa-names-zimcabinet-appoints-african-development-bank-vice-president-prof-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907183125/https://www.celebgossip.co.za/international-news/5148-mnangagwa-names-zimcabinet-appoints-african-development-bank-vice-president-prof-mthuli-ncube-as-finance-minister.html |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nBefore joining the bank, he was dean and professor of finance at [[Wits Business School]] and then dean of the faculty of Commerce, Law and Management at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] (Wits) as well as a lecturer in finance at the [[London School of Economics]].\n\nHe has published a number of award-winning papers{{Citation needed|reason=What awards?|date=January 2019}} in the area of finance and economics as well as a number of books including, ''Mathematical Finance: Option and Asset Pricing'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=2010 |title=Mathematical Finance: Option and Asset Pricing |location=Sandton, Johannesburg, South Africa |publisher=Heinemann |isbn=978-0-7962-3386-8}}, no reviews found.</ref> ''South African Dictionary of Finance'' (editor);<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wuite |first=Rudy |year=2009 |editor-last=Ncube |editor-first=Mthuli |title=South African Dictionary of Finance |location=Northcliff, South Africa |publisher=Rollerbird Press |isbn=978-1-920334-02-4}}</ref> ''Financial Systems and Monetary Policy in Africa'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=2008 |title=Financial Systems and Monetary Policy in Africa |location=Nairobi, Kenya |publisher=African Economic Research Consortium |isbn=978-9966-778-30-7}}, no reviews found.</ref> ''Development Dynamics: Theories and Lessons from Zimbabwe'';<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ncube |first=Mthuli |year=1991 |title=Development Dynamics: Theories and Lessons from Zimbabwe |location= Aldershot, Haunts, England |publisher=Avebury |isbn=978-1-85628-087-7}}, no reviews found.</ref> and ''Monetary Policy and the Economy in South Africa'' (with Eliphas Ndou).<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Ncube |first1=Mthuli |last2=Ndou |first2=Eliphas |year=2013 |title=Monetary Policy and the Economy in South Africa |location=London |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-137-33414-5}}</ref>\n\nNcube is currently a visiting professor at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"Oxford\">{{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube, visiting professor 2017\u20132020 |publisher=University of Oxford |url=https://www.bsg.ox.ac.uk/people/mthuli-ncube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029025413/https://www.bsg.ox.ac.uk/people/mthuli-ncube |archive-date=29 October 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n==Work at the African Development Bank==\nNcube was the Chief Economist and Vice President of the [[African Development Bank]] (AfDB).<ref name=\"Oxford\" /> As Chief Economist, he oversaw the Economics Complex, which is focused on the process of knowledge management within the Bank and with its partners, and general strategic economic research within the Bank. In this regard, he supervised the Development Research Department, Statistics Department and African Development Institute. As a Vice President, Professor Mthuli Ncube was a member of the senior management team of the Bank and contributed to its general strategic direction.<ref name=\"Banda\" />\n\n==Other work==\nNcube was also a regulator and a board member of the [[South African Financial Services Board]] (FSB), which regulates non-bank financial institutions in South Africa, founding  chairman of [[Barbican and Selwyn Capital]] and worked for [[Investec]] Asset Management as a Portfolio Manager and Head of Asset Allocation Strategy.<ref name=\"Oxford\" />\n\nNcube has also been Chairman of the Board of the [[African Economic Research Consortium]],<ref name=\"Vibrant-Bio\">{{Cite web|title=Mthuli Ncube, Vice President and Chief Economist |date=2012 |work=Distinguished Lecture Series |publisher=Vibrant Media |location=Johannesburg, South Africa |url=http://www.vibrantmedia.co.za/m/wbs/12/DistinguishedLectureSeries/DLS_MthuliNcube/bio.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109044039/http://www.vibrantmedia.co.za/m/wbs/12/DistinguishedLectureSeries/DLS_MthuliNcube/bio.pdf |archive-date=9 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> chairman of the Global Agenda Council on \"Poverty and Economic Development\" ([[World Economic Forum]]) and a governor of the [[African Capacity Building Foundation]].{{fact|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Finance Minister==\nNcube was appointed Minister of Finance in Zimbabwe on Friday 7 September 2018 under President Emmerson Mnangagwa's government.<ref name=\"Dzirutwe\" /><ref name=\"Banda\" />  In 2019, he presided over the conversion from foreign currency to a [[RTGS dollar|new Zimbabwean currency]], and the resultant return of [[Hyperinflation in Zimbabwe|hyper-inflation]].<ref name=\"Mordasov\">{{Cite news|last=Mordasov |first=Pavel |date=9 October 2019 |title=The Return of Hyperinflation in Zimbabwe |newspaper=Mises Wire |publisher=Mises Institute |location=Auburn, Alabama |url=https://mises.org/wire/return-hyperinflation-zimbabwe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011051941/https://mises.org/wire/return-hyperinflation-zimbabwe |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Amin\">{{Cite news|last=Amin |first=Haslinda |title=At More Than 500%, Zimbabwe\u2019s Ncube Sees Inflation Stabilizing |date=22 January 2020 |newspaper=Bloomberg News |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/at-more-than-500-zimbabwe-s-ncube-sees-inflation-stabilizing |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226133208/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/at-more-than-500-zimbabwe-s-ncube-sees-inflation-stabilizing |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vinga |first=Alois |date=26 January 2020 |title=Ncube scorned for Davos claims Zim economy recovering |newspaper=New Zimbabwe |url=https://www.newzimbabwe.com/ncube-scorned-for-davos-claims-zim-economy-recovering/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126101330/https://www.newzimbabwe.com/ncube-scorned-for-davos-claims-zim-economy-recovering/ |archive-date=26 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Ncube suspended publishing inflation data after June 2019,<ref name=\"Amin\"/> and in October 2019 he indicated inflation figures for Zimbabwe would again be released in February 2020.<ref name=\"Mordasov\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nNcube is married and has four children.<ref name=\"Vibrant-Bio\" />\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.afdb.org/en/knowledge/economics-research/our-researchers/mthuli-ncube/ Profile at the African Development Bank]\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ncube, Mthuli}}\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand academics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:South African economists]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:2278:4c00:a97d:aaae:2cf0:2d86", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mthuli_Ncube"}
